 Synchronous programming is a type of programming where the code execution follows a sequence of statements in a linear fashion. In other words, it involves blocking the UI thread while executing the code. This means that any other activity happening outside of the code or within the UI will be paused until the code is complete. 

For example, if you were to execute the following code:

```
// code block to execute synchronously
let x = 5;
console.log(x);
```

The `console.log()` statement will execute first, and then the execution of the code block will continue with the variable `x` being set to `5`. 

Asynchronous programming, on the other hand, is a type of programming where the code execution does not block the UI thread while executing the code. This means that any other activity happening outside of the code can continue while the code is executed. 

For example, if you were to execute the following code:

```
// code block to execute asynchronously
setTimeout(() => {
 console.log("code executed");
}, 1000);
```

The `setTimeout()` function will execute after a delay of 1 second, and the code block will then continue executing after the delay has passed. In this case, the console.log() statement will be executed within the setTimeout() function and will not block the UI thread until the code block is complete.
